    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-08-14T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-08-14T02:00:00-05:00" n="680"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d680">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">741.94/499: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Greta</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-08-14T16:00:00+09:00"
                            >August 14, 1941—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 14—7:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1236. This telegram refers to Embassy’s No. 1235, August 14, 3 p.m.<note n="25"
                        xml:id="d680fn25">Not printed.</note> sent air mail to Shanghai reporting in
                    full the British Ambassador’s interview with the Japanese Foreign Minister<note
                        n="26" xml:id="d680fn26">Adm. Teijiro Toyoda.</note> on August 11.</p>
                <p>In summarizing his conclusion and impressions of his interview with the Foreign
                    Minister my British colleague in a telegram dated August 12 reported to the
                    Foreign Office in London: <pb facs="0865" n="857" xml:id="pg_857"/>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <list>
                            <item>“1. That as a result of his interview with Admiral Toyoda and a
                                brief conversation which he had held immediately prior thereto with
                                the Minister’s interpreter he was convinced that Admiral Toyoda
                                remained reasonably well disposed towards Great Britain and was
                                sincerely desirous insofar as the situation would permit of
                                preventing a break with Great Britain.</item>
                            <item>2. That he was more than ever convinced that the policy of
                                ‘keeping Japan guessing’ was a mistake under present conditions and
                                that there was more to be gained by a frank and open discussion of
                                mutual difficulties.</item>
                            <item>3. That it was significant that no mention was made throughout the
                                entire interview of the United States.</item>
                            <item>4. That the Minister of Foreign Affairs made no complaint
                                concerning the freezing of Japanese assets by Great Britain and
                                confined his remarks in this regard to the dangers of further
                                restriction of exports to Japan on the part of the Dutch East
                                Indies.[”]</item>
                        </list>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
